{
  "message": "chore: move per-bead progress reports into docs/progress/\n\nTwenty-seven small markdown files at the workspace root recorded\nper-bead work logs from earlier development sessions. They were\nmostly 1-3 KB each and described what got done on a given bead in a\ngiven day, with timestamps, log excerpts, and follow-up notes:\n\n- progress.md: top-level catch-all progress log\n- progress_bd-1333e.md, progress_bd-1dp9.6.7.8.4.md, progress_bd-1ge41.md,\n  progress_bd-1sf8n.md, progress_bd-1x82v.md, progress_bd-23yu4.md,\n  progress_bd-2l5jk.md, progress_bd-2wt.2.md, progress_bd-3wop3.1.2.md,\n  progress_bd-abgqx.md, progress_bd-c0bsc.md, progress_bd-c9pxw.md,\n  progress_bd-dwyer.md, progress_bd-gieaf.md, progress_bd-iuvw4.md,\n  progress_bd-nsvud.md, progress_bd-o023g.md, progress_bd-obixt.md,\n  progress_bd-ooc2c.md, progress_bd-t6sv2.10.md, progress_bd-t6sv2.8.md,\n  progress_bd-udl9m.md: per-bead progress logs (April 2026 burst)\n- bd-1cs00.md, bd-1cs00.1.md, bd-1cs00.2.md, bd-1cs00.3.md: structured\n  planning documents for the asupersync runtime integration (a deep\n  cross-cutting refactor that preceded its own beads)\n\nThese files have residual reference value because they capture *why*\na particular slice was scoped the way it was, and what was tried that\nfailed before what shipped \u2014 context that the closing-comment in the\nbeads database alone does not preserve. But they don't belong at the\nrepo root where they overwhelm the project-level documentation; the\ntypical visitor lands and sees 27 progress_bd-*.md files and concludes\nthe project is unstructured.\n\nMove them to docs/progress/ verbatim. Filenames preserved so any\nexisting links continue to resolve via a path prefix update. The .gitignore\nalready covers /SESSION_*.md, /repro_*.rs, etc. for future scratch;\nthis move + the existing rules close that loop.\n\nIf the work-log content turns out to be redundant with the beads\ndatabase itself, a future commit can prune the directory wholesale \u2014\nkeeping them git-mv'd preserves history if that decision needs to be\nreversed.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>",
